The generator wraps every path-parameter substitution in net/url's
PathEscape, which percent-encodes everything outside RFC 3986's
"unreserved" set. That includes "(" and ")".

VRChat instance IDs canonically contain literal parens, e.g.

    20848~group(grp_abc)~groupAccessType(public)~region(use)

When the SDK escapes those to "%28" / "%29" Cloudflare's WAF rejects the
request with HTTP 400 and waf_code 26497 ("malformed url"), so every
group-instance lookup fails 100% of the time.

Per RFC 3986 section 3.3, path segments are defined as

    pchar = unreserved / pct-encoded / sub-delims / ":" / "@"

and parens are in sub-delims — they're legal unencoded. Go's
url.PathEscape is intentionally over-conservative (documented as "the
conservative interpretation of unreserved"), so the generated code needs
a less-aggressive helper instead.

Patch: rewrite every "url.PathEscape(x)" call in api_*.go files to
"pathSegmentEscape(x)". The helper lives in path_escape.go (a
hand-written file at the repo root that the generator never touches) and
encodes per the pchar production above, leaving parens and tildes alone
while still percent-encoding "/", "#", spaces, control bytes, etc.

Leave the "net/url" import in place — those files still use url.Values{}
for query parameters.
